<span id="freeTextContainer3034304264992148926">I am a huge fan of Sharon Kay Penman&apos;s, and &quot;Time and Chance&quot; did not disappoint, though I found it harder to get through than some of her other works, such as &quot;Lionheart&quot; and &quot;The Sunne in Splendour&quot;. I would definitely recommend reading this one close to its predecessor, &quot;When Christ and His Saints Slept&quot;, as I waited two years in between the two and some of the story lines had been lost to the mists of time for me. I very much love Penman&apos;s attention to detail, however, and I especially appre</span>
  <span id="freeText3034304264992148926" style="display:none">I am a huge fan of Sharon Kay Penman's, and "Time and Chance" did not disappoint, though I found it harder to get through than some of her other works, such as "Lionheart" and "The Sunne in Splendour". I would definitely recommend reading this one close to its predecessor, "When Christ and His Saints Slept", as I waited two years in between the two and some of the story lines had been lost to the mists of time for me. I very much love Penman's attention to detail, however, and I especially appreciate her original character, Ranulf, uncle to King Henry II-- I regret that he too was not a historical figure! Overall I would highly recommend "Time and Chance" for its beautiful, detailed writing. </span>
